│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe provided reproducer crashes under MemorySSA     │
│ verification during loop rotation. The assertion \"Memory Def does not        │
│ dominate it's uses\" indicates that after CFG/IR transformations, MemorySSA's │
│ def-use and dominance invariants were broken. In this pipeline, LoopRotate    │
│ performs cloning and edge updates, and MemorySSAUpdater is expected to keep   │
│ MemorySSA consistent. A common source of such failures is when the IR is      │
│ mutated in ways that affect MemorySSA before MemorySSAUpdater has a chance to │
│ account for those changes.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log:\n- The debug log      │
│ shows MemorySSA clobber info for stores both pre- and post-unswitch, then the │
│ LoopRotation phase starts.\n- Right before the crash, LoopRotation reports    │
│ \"Folding loop latch for.inc into for.latch\" and then proceeds to rotate a   │
│ loop. The crash occurs at the first verifyMemorySSA triggered inside          │
│ rotateLoop (stack shows verifyMemorySSA called from                           │
│ LoopRotationUtils.cpp:833).\n- In the rotateLoop code region, we see:\n  -    │
│ Lines 786-790: PHI nodes in each successor of OrigHeader are updated by       │
│ adding incoming values for OrigPreheader.\n  - Lines 799-803:                 │
│ MemorySSAUpdater (MSSAU) is invoked: InsertNewValueIntoMap and                │
│ updateForClonedBlockIntoPred.\n  - Then DT updates and verifyMemorySSA, which │
│ triggers the assertion.\nThis ordering is suspicious: IR PHI modifications    │
│ are done before MemorySSAUpdater has updated MSSA to reflect the cloned       │
│ block's memory accesses and new edges.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nMemorySSA  │
│ maintains Def-Use chains and relies on CFG dominance to ensure that every     │
│ MemoryUse/Def is dominated by its clobbering MemoryDef/Phi. In rotateLoop,    │
│ the code first duplicates OrigHeader's terminator into OrigPreheader, and     │
│ then immediately \"fixes up\" the successor PHI nodes by adding incoming      │
│ values for OrigPreheader (lines 786-790). This mutates the IR (value PHIs) on │
│ successors to have new incoming values from OrigPreheader while MemorySSA     │
│ still reflects the pre-update state for the edge and cloned memory            │
│ accesses.\n\nBecause MemorySSAUpdater hasn't yet been called to register the  │
│ cloned block's memory accesses and to update MemorySSA PHIs along new edges,  │
│ the verifier sees uses reachable via the newly added IR PHI incomings that    │
│ correspond to memory accesses dominated poorly in the MemorySSA graph. The    │
│ subsequent call to MSSAU->updateForClonedBlockIntoPred occurs after IR has    │
│ been changed and may not correctly account for the prior PHI incoming         │
│ modifications, leading to a temporary or final inconsistency that triggers    │
│ the dominance assertion during verifyMemorySSA right after DT updates.\n\nIn  │
│ short, the ordering of operations breaks MemorySSA's assumptions: IR PHI      │
│ incoming edges are updated before MemorySSA is updated for the cloned block   │
│ and new predecessor edge, causing def-use mismatch.\n\n4. Proposed Edit       │
│ Point(s):\n- Move the PHI fix-up loop (lines 786-790) to occur after          │
│ MemorySSA is updated for the cloned block and edge. That is, ensure           │
│ MSSAU->InsertNewValueIntoMap and MSSAU->updateForClonedBlockIntoPred run      │
│ before altering successor PHI nodes' incoming values.\n- Concretely, relocate │
│ the block:\n  for (BasicBlock *SuccBB : successors(OrigHeader))\n    for      │
│ (BasicBlock::iterator BI = SuccBB->begin();\n         PHINode *PN =           │
│ dyn_cast<PHINode>(BI); ++BI)\n                                                │
│ PN->addIncoming(PN->getIncomingValueForBlock(OrigHeader),                     │
│ OrigPreheader);\nfrom lines 786-790 to just after the MSSAU update block at   │
│ 799-803. This ensures MemorySSA has been brought up to date with the cloned   │
│ block into predecessor before IR PHIs get new incoming edges, keeping         │
│ MemorySSA def-use/dominance consistent when verifyMemorySSA runs.\n\nEdit     │
│ details:\n- File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopRotationUtils.cpp\n- Lines    │
│ 786-803: Reorder so that the MSSAU update block (799-803) comes first,        │
│ followed by the PHI fix-up loop.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash is caused by    │
│ updating successor PHI incoming edges before MemorySSA is updated to reflect  │
│ the cloned block and new predecessor relationship, violating MemorySSA        │
│ dominance invariants. By moving the PHI fix-up after MemorySSAUpdater's       │
│ updateForClonedBlockIntoPred (and its value map insertion), we preserve a     │
│ correct update ordering: first update MemorySSA to reflect CFG/IR cloning,    │
│ then adjust IR PHIs. This should eliminate the assertion during               │
│ verifyMemorySSA in rotateLoop and maintain consistent MemorySSA state         │
│ throughout the rotation."})                                                   │
